2.(Where do you buy a house in Chicago?) The crime data of Chicago are publicly available here link Take the subset of crimes commited in 2015 and plot a red dot (with enough transparency) for each theft appeared during 2015 until today on googlemap. Hint: Use get map, and ggmap functions from ggmap library to download the google map with appropriate zoom, longitude, and latitude. Then add red points using geom point function of ggplot2 library with transparency on your Chicago map. See the sample of the next page. PS: Using ggplot functions is not straightforward, check some simple examples first, before trying to overlay your points on the map.

library(MASS)
require(ggplot2)
require(ggmap)
D=read.csv("C:/Users/BABAK/Desktop/Crimes.csv",header = TRUE)
lon=D$Longitude
lat=D$Latitude
mymap= get_map(location="chicago",zoom=11,scale="auto",maptype="roadmap")
ggmap(mymap)+
  geom_point(data=as.data.frame(cbind(lon,lat)),aes(x=D$Longitude,y=D$Latitude),color="red",alpha=.6,size=1,shape=21)

  1. Plot the univariate density of thefts of 2015 over latitude plot(density()) the sample of the next page.
require(ggplot2)
require(ggmap)
D=read.csv("C:/Users/BABAK/Desktop/Crimes.csv",header = TRUE)
lon=D$Longitude
lat=D$Latitude
plot(density(na.omit(D)$Latitude),xlab="latitude",col="blue",main="Density over latitude")

4.Compute he 2D density using kde2d function of library MASS and use persp function to provide a 3D plot. See the sample of the next page.

library(MASS)
require(ggplot2)
require(ggmap)
D=read.csv("C:/Users/BABAK/Desktop/Crimes.csv",header = TRUE)
lon=D$Longitude
lat=D$Latitude
persp(kde2d(na.omit(D)$Latitude,na.omit(D)$Longitude),phi = 45, theta = 0,
      xlab = "Lat", ylab = "Long",zlab = "density")
